Yo, listen up! I'm gonna be a social worker, ya know? Like, I wanna help out those kids who've been messed with, the ones who've had a rough go. And I wanna help out families who are, like, totally outta whack. See, I've got this whole set of values, like, service to others, treating everyone with respect, being straight up honest, always trying to make things better between people, and never stoppin' to learn and grow in my field. These values ain't just some fancy talk, they're deep down in my soul, man.

Ever since I was a kid, I always wanted to help folks out. But I wasn't sure how, ya know?  In high school and college, I saw a lot of people runnin' from their problems, some even doin' messed up things to cope. I saw some stuff that made me wanna do something, so I went for a psychology degree. But even after I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009, I was still lookin' for my groove. Then one day, this friend of mine introduced me to this sixteen year old kid who was totally stressed out. Turns out, he was runnin' from his abusive parents.  The next day, I found out he called the cops on 'em!  I felt like I had to do something, so I went to his parents' house and talked to the cops. They asked me to talk to the parents since there wasn't much they could do for the kid. When I asked 'em about it, they were all nervous and makin' excuses, sayin' the kid was just manipulatin' them. It blew my mind! That's when I really started thinkin' about social work, about helpin' these kids with their family drama.

Another big thing for me is social justice.  Society always goes on about how important individuals are, but then they act like we're all supposed to be the same. It's like, if we're all so unique, why are we tryin' to fit in so hard? I'm my own person, and I ain't gonna let anyone tell me how to be. Through high school and college, I fought against injustice whenever I could.  Colored my hair crazy colors, wore what I wanted, pierced my ears, joined the Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance, spoke up against racism and discrimination... I stand for social justice, man, and I'm gonna keep fightin' for it.

Alright, so lemme tell ya 'bout this sleep stuff. See, there's these two ways of lookin' at why folks can't sleep, like, *really* can't sleep. One way is all about the body, like what's goin' on inside ya, genes and stuff. Call it the "body's wired wrong" theory. The other way's about the world around ya, your fam, your friends, where ya live, that kinda thing. Call it the "life be a drag" theory. 

So, there's this thing called insomnia, where you can't fall asleep or stay asleep. It can come from all sorts of places. You got your basic sleep problems, like trouble fallin' asleep or sleepin' too much. Then you got your "brain's screwy" problems, where your mind's messed up and it messes with your sleep. And sometimes, it's 'cause of somethin' else, like a medical thing or something you popped. 

Now, the "body's wired wrong" folks, they say it's all about your genes, like if you got some bad sleep genes, you're doomed. And they point to this thing in your brain called the hypothalamus, which is like the sleep control center. See, there's these tiny things in your brain called neurons, and they send signals to tell you when to sleep and when to wake up. These neurons have these things called receptors, and if they ain't workin' right, you might have trouble sleepin'.  

They did this study with mice, see, and they found that these receptors can make you sleepy. If you mess with 'em, you might wake up, and if you mess with 'em the other way, you might sleep even more. So they're sayin' that maybe if people have messed up receptors, that's why they can't sleep.

The "life be a drag" folks, they say it's all about your life, your stress, your job, your fam, that kinda thing. If you're stressed out or worried or lonely, you might have trouble sleepin'. 

They don't have any studies about mice, though.

Alright, so listen up! This here's the lowdown on this thing called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD for short. 

First off, lemme tell ya what it is. Basically, it's like your brain's got a problem understanding what it hears, even if your ears are just fine. Think of it like this: you hear the words, but your brain's gotta kinda scramble 'em around to make sense of 'em.

Now, to figure out if someone's got CAPD, there are a few things we look for. It's like a bunch of red flags, ya know? Like, maybe they can't tell where a sound's coming from, or they get mixed up when there's a lot of noise goin' on. They might have trouble tellin' apart different sounds, or understandin' when someone's sayin' somethin' sarcastically.

So, what can ya do if you're a teacher and one of your students has CAPD? Well, there are a few tricks you can use to help 'em out. It's all about makin' things a little clearer and easier for their brain to process.

So, this play, *Twelfth Night*, kinda makes you think about how disguises are cool for tricking people, but if you keep pretending to be someone you're not, you might lose yourself for good!  The problem is, when you stop pretending, you might mess things up with the people you've been fooling.  

Like, some folks might not care that you lied, but others will be totally ticked off. It's a tough choice, gotta decide if you gotta protect yourself or keep your friends happy.

This whole gender-bending thing is extra tricky, ya know? Why do people want to pretend to be the opposite gender? In Viola's case, she's just trying to stay safe in a new land. She tells us, "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” 

Being a girl in a strange place is risky business, so she puts on a guy costume. But now she can't hang with the other girls, and she's cut off from their support.

To make it even weirder, Olivia falls head over heels for her, thinking she's a guy named Cesario. She's like, "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.”

And then there's Orsino, who kinda has the hots for Viola but she's hiding it. He's all, "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.”

So, maybe this play is saying that pretending can help us figure out our real feelings, even if it's messy. Olivia and Orsino are forced to deal with stuff they might not have admitted to themselves.

Is Olivia into Cesario 'cause he's a guy, or is she secretly into girls?  Maybe she's just messing with people, showing how shallow people can be back then.

She ditches Cesario for Sebastian in a heartbeat and treats Cesario/Viola like family, like, "A sister, you are she.”

Alright, lemme tell ya 'bout this German place, South West Africa. Now, lemme tell ya, not all Germans were bad, but this one time, they got real messy. They did some awful things, especially to the Ovaherero and Nama people. It was bad news, real bad. But hey, Germany wasn't all bad, ya know? They had different ways of doin' things in different places. Like, when the Brits took over their East Africa bit, they found a bunch of smart folks who already knew how to read and write. Germans were even praised for how they did things in Kamerun and other places.

But in South West Africa, things were different.  Imagine this: instead of buildin' schools for the locals, they kinda left that to the churches. The churches tried, but they didn't have much help from the government. Now, the Germans did love to educate their own people though. They built fancy schools for them and helped the churches out with their schools too.

This messed things up for South West Africa. While other German places had lots of smart folks, South West Africa stayed mostly behind.  A lot of people couldn't read or write. Why? That's what this whole story is about. We gotta look at how the settlers and the bosses felt about the local people.

There's a whole bunch of books written about German schools back in the day. Most are in German, which is a pain, but some folks figured out what they were sayin' and wrote about it in English. They noticed that every place was different, like comparing apples and oranges.  One guy, Cohen, wrote about South West Africa and East Africa. He figured out that the big farmer crowd in South West Africa was a big reason why things were different there.

South West Africa, even though it was kinda hot and dry, had a lot of white settlers. By 1913, it had more white folks than any other German colony except for East Africa.

So, man, you know how music's like, super varied these days? It's wild! Like, there's tons of genres, right?  Rock, rap, country, jazz, folk... and each one has a million little categories inside of it.  It's like a big, crazy musical family reunion.  But you know what's really blown up? Heavy Metal.  It's been around for a while, but it's gone through so many changes, it's like it's its own universe now! 

It's wild how much different heavy metal can be. One minute it's dark and intense, the next it's all fast and furious.  And get this, people have been breaking it down into even smaller pieces, like sub-genres within sub-genres. It's like musical Russian nesting dolls! 

It's gotten so crazy that sometimes I don't even know what counts as heavy metal anymore.  It's got a little bit of everything in it! But that's what makes it so cool.  It's like a melting pot of sounds, you know?

But to really get it, you gotta understand where it came from. Heavy metal isn't just music; it's a whole vibe, a movement. It's all about that heavy, dark energy. More bass, more volume, more passion, more everything!  

People think metal is all about drugs and craziness, and yeah, there's definitely some truth to that. Back in the 70s, everyone was experimenting, and that influence totally seeped into the music. But it's also about that raw, primal emotion that gets unleashed when you crank up the amps.  It's like tapping into something deep inside yourself.

Even the lyrics are intense.  Like, remember that Beatles song, "Helter Skelter"?  It's dark, chaotic, and kind of scary. Some folks think it was one of the first heavy metal songs!

Metal is definitely a journey, man. It's a wild ride, full of twists and turns.  But if you're brave enough to jump in, you might just find yourself blown away.

Man, you wouldn't believe this dream I had! It was like, totally surreal, just like those paintings those fancy art folks do.  But get this, this whole dream thing was going on way back when this dude, Henri Rousseau, was painting.  He wasn't just painting regular stuff, he was painting his dreams, you know? Like, he wanted everyone to see his dreams.

This painting he did, called "The Dream," is about this lady checking out some crazy stuff in a dreamland. But it's also about Rousseau's own dreams, like wanting people to think his art was awesome.  Problem was, he was kinda stuck.  He wanted everyone to like his stuff, but he also wanted to do his own thing.

So, here's the deal with this guy: he wasn't born with a silver spoon, he worked hard, like a real regular guy.  He wasn't some fancy art school graduate, he just loved painting.  He had this rough time, lost his wife and kids, and painting was his escape.

He wanted to be like those famous artists everyone was talking about, but they were all doing their own thing.  Rousseau was like, "Hey, I want to paint something cool that people will like!" But he also knew he had to stay true to himself. It was a real struggle, man!

This guy Gordon wrote this book about French artists, and he said Rousseau wanted to paint something so normal, so everyone would think he was cool.  But Matisse, he was all about being different and not painting anything boring.

It was like two different sides of the same coin, you know? Both trying to make it in the art world, but in totally different ways.

Lotsa brainy folks have said that ethics and art are like BFFs, ya know? Like, truth and beauty are totally connected. It's like, what John Keats said in his poem 'Ode on a Grecian Urn', "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."  We learn a lot from school and stuff, but things like right and wrong, and what's beautiful, just kinda...click for us, ya know? 

Keats is onto somethin'. Ethics and art are more about explainin' why somethin' is good or beautiful, instead of makin' a big set of rules about it. Like, when people talk about why a painting is awesome, they might talk about the colors and stuff, but that doesn't really capture the *magic* of it. When you ask someone about their favorite book or movie, they'll say somethin' like, "There's just somethin' about it," before they try to explain it. It's like, there's this extra somethin' that can't be put into words. 

Same thing with morals! You can talk about all the rules and stuff, but there's this deeper level that just *is*. Like Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." You can't explain it all, there's always somethin' left over.

I think that's why art and morals are so connected. They both hit us in this deep, feel-good way that we can't really explain. Especially with books, they get right into our hearts and make us think about life and stuff. Like, they're kinda like life itself!

Today's Germany is a real powerhouse, a united country with its own special flavor, from the mountains around München all the way to the coast in Kiel.  You can feel that same energy from Köln on the Rhine River, right through the heart of the country, all the way to Dresden in Saxony on the Elbe. It's no surprise that Germany's culture is so unique, since it came from all sorts of different groups and tribes. 

There's this place called Germania, where the Germans came from. Nobody can really agree on where the name came from. This guy Tacitus said it was from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought with the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar was the first to use the word "Germanus" when he was writing about his battles with the Gauls and the Germanic tribes who kept crossing the Rhine (Caesar, 50-40 BC).  He took the word from the Gauls themselves, so they could tell the difference between them, the conquered, and the Germans, who they hadn't conquered yet. Some people think it means "neighbor" in Gaulish. In the first book of his Gallic Wars, Caesar writes "The Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war." (Caesar, 50-40 BC). Others think it comes from the spear they used in battle, called a "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or maybe from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," meaning the Germans were loud and noisy (Names of Germany).

This Roman guy named Tacitus, who wrote a book about the Germans in AD 98 called "De Origine et situ Germanorum," said he thought the Germans were the original people there and hadn't mixed with other races (Tacitus, 98). He said, "I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?"

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Not the Romans, not yet anyway. They would send their armies into Germania to get stuff and fight some battles, but mostly they went back home to their big empire. So as the Germanic tribes started showing up in the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, traded their stuff they got from the land, and even fought for the Romans in their army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

Man, this thing was messed up. I stared at it for a minute, tryin' to figure out what was going on. My brain was workin' overtime, but I couldn't quite make sense of it. It was like lookin' at a bowl of spaghetti and tryin' to figure out the meaning of life. 

Remember that art book I got? "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain"?  It said somethin' about usin' a mental frame to simplify what you're seein'.  Like, instead of lookin' at a whole kitchen, you just focus on the bowl of fruit.  But this? This was too much, even for that trick.

I mean, Picasso had his blue phase, Monet loved his greens, and those Renaissance guys went wild with colors. If I was gonna be an artist, this was my masterpiece.  My masterpiece in brown.

I reached for my tool, my weapon of choice in this artistic battle.  Tightened my grip, visualized the flow, and...whacked the handle of the toilet. Water swirled, stuff broke off, drifted away.  Kinda peaceful, actually.

But then the darn thing wouldn't budge!  Stuck like glue.  

Mop in hand, tie feelin' tighter than a drum, I stared at this brown abomination.  A message, I guess, from the person who left it.  A message for the poor saps who had to clean up after 'em.

A couple more flushes, a few more moments of zen, and I grabbed the toilet paper.  Wrapped myself up like a mummy.  Like a turkey goin' into the oven.

You know, it's crazy how many young folks are gettin' wrecked behind the wheel. It's like, their brains ain't even ready for all that traffic chaos!  Those brainiacs over at the National Institutes of Health say it's a real thing. You got all these new drivers with zero experience, zippin' around like they own the place. No wonder they crash more, speed like maniacs, and end up flipping their cars!

And don't even get me started on teen passengers! It's like they can't go anywhere without their buddies crammed in the car.  Some smart folks down at the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center did a study, and guess what? More passengers mean more fender benders. 

So, some states are tryin' to fix things with these "provisional" licenses.  They put limits on when ya can drive and who you can ride with. But come on, that's just a bandaid on a bullet hole! The real problem is that young drivers are just too dang immature to handle the wheel! This psychologist, Marvin Zuckerman, says even 18 is too young!  He did some research and figured out that kids under 20 are all about that thrill-seeking life. So, makin' 'em wait a bit longer to drive, until they calm down a bit, sounds like a good idea, right?

We gotta stop giving licenses to kids who are just lookin' for a rush! Otherwise, those car crash stats are gonna skyrocket when all those Baby Boomer grandkids are old enough to drive.  

Here's what we gotta do: schools can still teach 'em about driving, but nobody under 18 can hit the road.  They can get a learner's permit beforehand and still do all that practice stuff, like the 6 hours behind the wheel and 50 hours with a grown-up that California does.  We need to make these rules the same everywhere, so everyone's on the same page. It's a simple fix, and it'll save a ton of lives!

Besides, this ain't nothin' new.

So, I was checking out this old pile of movies at the Library of Congress, all these early Edison flicks. They had fifteen of these "trick films" from way back when, between 1895 and 1901.  These movies were all about tricking your eyes, using clever editing to make stuff look crazy. I figured I'd take a peek and see what was up.  

Most of these trick films were pretty simple, stuck in one spot, like they were on a stage.  No fancy camera moves, just plain old shots, no getting up close and personal with anyone.  They'd just point the camera and shoot, over and over. It was like watching a magic show, but without the tricksy music.

These movies were all filmed inside, like a little stage set. The camera never moved, just watched what was happening in front of it.  Think of a play, but with less acting and more weird stuff happening.

They’d stick to long shots, sometimes medium shots, but never any close-ups. It's like they were trying to show you the whole darn thing at once, no matter how small the detail. It's like they wanted you to feel like you were right there in the middle of the action, but stuck in the front row.

And get this, they'd make one idea, one trick, into one whole movie. That means a lot of these trick films were super short, like a minute or less. They couldn’t really tell a story, just show off a quick magic trick or make someone disappear.

But here's the sneaky part: even though they pretended it was all one shot, they secretly used multiple takes to make the illusions work.  Take this one movie, "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots," for example.  Looks like one shot, right? But if you look really close, you can see how they made the head disappear.  They were like sneaky ninjas of the film world!

Alright, so there's this dude, John Taylor, from back in the day. This guy was all about being a farmer and keeping things simple. He was super into this whole "Republicanism" thing, ya know?  He thought the government should keep its paws off people's lives, especially when it came to stuff like farming.  He even got into politics for a bit, but it didn't last long. This guy was a straight shooter, always speaking his mind about freedom and how the government shouldn't mess with folks.

He believed that America had a real chance to do things right, 'cause we didn't have any old traditions messing things up.  We could build a government from scratch,  based on people's natural rights.  He was all about those rights, you know, like the right to life, liberty, and stuff like that.  He thought those rights were super important, and if one got messed with, they all started to crumble.  

To make this dream of a perfect society happen, John thought we needed a government that understood both the good and bad in people. He was pretty hardcore about this "good vs. evil" thing. He was like, "Governments are run by people, so they're gonna have both good and bad parts."  He thought good governments protect your stuff, help out farmers, and keep big business in check.  He figured if you built a government on those ideas, it would work even if the people running it were kinda greedy.

John believed everyone's always lookin' out for themselves, but that's not always a bad thing. It's only a problem when people get greedy and start taking advantage of others.  A good government, he said, needs to keep those greedy folks in line and make sure everyone has a fair shot.

He and a bunch of other guys back then were all about sticking to the Constitution.  They wanted the government to stay small and only do the things it was specifically told to do.  They thought a big government was too expensive and could easily turn into a dictatorship. But he also said that just reading the Constitution like it was a boring textbook wouldn't work. You gotta look at what the guys who wrote it meant by it, ya know?  He even thought the Declaration of Independence was more important, 'cause it talked about states being more independent from each other.

Alright, so check it out. We had this thing, right? We were trying to get people to ditch their cars and use bikes or walk to campus.  See, Figure 17 shows that folks just stopped logging their commutes around the third month. Kinda bummer, y'know?  

We figured maybe it was the weather getting colder, less folks biking or walking. Plus, December is crazy busy with school stuff and the holidays everyone's outta here! Then January rolled around, and classes were back but still, not many log entries. What gives?  Maybe people just lost interest, like, all new projects have that initial hype, then it fizzles.

So, we cranked up the fun with "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, and guess what? More log entries!  So, the problem wasn't just the season, but keeping things exciting. 

But here's the real kicker: everyone loves their cars! Driving's like, ingrained in our culture.  So, we had to bribe 'em with prizes, like gift cards to places like restaurants, coffee shops, even a massage therapist! Would've been awesome to throw in a sweet bike, maybe even a hybrid or electric car, though. Think that would've gotten people pumped!

The prizes were pretty decent, but maybe if they got better throughout the project, we coulda kept the momentum going. Think folks would've gone nuts for a brand new car!

Yo, check it! So there's this thing called an ETF, right? It's like a basket of stocks, but instead of buying each stock individually, you just buy one ETF. Think of it like a shortcut to owning a bunch of companies at once.  

ETFs are pretty cool because they're cheaper to own than those old-school mutual funds. Plus, you can buy and sell them like regular stocks, which means you've got more options, like borrowing money to buy more (that's called "margin") or even betting against them (that's called "shorting"). Sounds wild, right?  

But hold up, there's a catch. You gotta pay a little fee every time you buy or sell an ETF, just like with regular stocks.  And while ETFs offer a bunch of different options, it's always a good idea to do your homework and make sure you're actually getting the diversification you think you are.

Let's take this ETF called IHF, for example. It's got a bunch of stocks inside it, but we're gonna focus on the top 10 because they make up most of the ETF.  We wanna see if owning those top 10 stocks directly would be better than just buying the whole ETF.

So, we crunched some numbers, and guess what? Just owning those top 10 stocks could actually give you a higher return and less risk! That means you could make more money and have less chance of losing it.

But wait, there's more! We gotta make sure these results aren't just a fluke. We gotta look at the "standard deviation," which basically tells us how much the prices of those stocks go up and down. If the standard deviation of those top 10 stocks is different from the ETF as a whole, then maybe owning the ETF is actually a better bet after all.

Alright, so check it out, this poem by Poe, "Dream-Land," is supposed to be one of his best, right?  Poe throws out this word "Thulé" a couple times, and some bookworm named Mabbott traced it back to some dude named Virgil. Virgil used it for this island way up north, beyond Britain, that the Greeks thought was like, the edge of everything. Virgil totally used the word, no doubt. But here's the thing: Poe was all about German writers, y'know?  

This whole "Thulé" thing makes me think Poe was hangin' with Goethe's stuff, big time. There's this author, Karl J. Arndt, who wrote this book about Poe and Goethe, and he totally compares their poems, saying Poe ripped off Goethe's style. 

Now, Goethe, he was a bigshot writer, known for this play "Faust." It's got two parts, the first one came out in 1808, and the second one, right before Goethe kicked the bucket in 1832. Inside that second part of "Faust" is a short poem called "The King of Thulé." It's about this king who loses his wife and goes totally bonkers. She gave him this goblet, and after she dies, he's drowning his sorrows in it. He gets all gloomy and decides to join his wife in the great beyond. He gives all his stuff to his kids but keeps the goblet. Then, he goes to a cliff, throws the goblet in the ocean, closes his eyes, and, boom, he's gone.

This king in "The King of Thulé" sounds a lot like the guy in Poe's "Dream-Land," maybe like a dark twin of Poe's own messed-up life and his love for drinkin'. "Faust" also got turned into a play by this dude H.P. Grattan in 1842, just before Poe used "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe only uses "Thulé" twice in his writing, once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land." It's like bookends, man. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about this gloomy place, Thulé. It's dark, lonely, he's haunted by dead friends, and everything's gray and colorless. It's like stepping right into Goethe's "The King of Thulé," where the king's lost his wife, he's alone, and he's lost his fire.

Goethe was a big deal, and Poe would have known him, especially since he was a fan of Tennyson.  Poe even said he admired Tennyson. And since everyone was copying Goethe back then, Poe would have definitely been exposed to his work.

Okay, so picture this: there's this lady, Jennifer Palmer, who went to this store, D&D Markets, right? Well, she slipped and fell on a whole mess of applesauce, and now she's all messed up. She's saying that the store manager, this guy Paul Martin, totally messed up, and she wants to hit him where it hurts - with some serious penalties. 

Now, to get those extra damages, she's gotta prove that Martin wasn't just careless, he was downright mean. Like, he knew about the spill, twice, even, but he was too busy stuffing his face with dinner to clean it up! Can you believe that?  

Apparently, this wasn't the first time something like this happened.  There were like, tons of other people who slipped and fell at D&D that year. So, Jennifer's saying Martin should've known better. This whole thing makes you wonder if Martin was just being a jerk, right? 

It all went down on a Friday afternoon. One of the employees, Rich Wayne, told Martin about the applesauce disaster.  But Martin was all, "nah, I'm eating, deal with it yourself." Another worker, Mary Haddigan, tried again, but Martin gave her the same rude response.  Then, boom!  Jennifer went down, broke her back, and now she's suing.

So, the question is, was Martin really malicious, or was he just a clueless manager? We'll have to see what the judge thinks.

Alright, listen up, cuz I gotta spill the tea about this Islam class I took back in the day, like, four years ago.  We were always arguing about whether Islam was, y'know, a bad religion or not.  And honestly, it feels even more important to talk about now than ever.  

After 9/11, things got crazy. The media went from totally hating on Islam and anyone who wasn't, like, a cookie-cutter American to being all, "Islam is amazing!"  It's crazy how fast things flipped.  I mean, back in 2001, could you imagine a president named Barack Obama, a dude with a Muslim family history?  No way!

But this whole thing about Muhammad's life...that's what really messes with my head.  See, I thought he was this hardcore conqueror who just forced people to become Muslim.  Take over tribes, boom, they're all Muslims now, right?  But this biography paints him as a total martyr, like some misunderstood dude who was just chillin' and people came to him on their own.  It's like, "Whoa, hold up!  That's not the Muhammad I thought I knew!"

And don't even get me started on the similarities between Muhammad and Jesus.  Like, the whole feeding the crowds thing?  Totally ripped off from Jesus, but somehow it's supposed to make Muhammad look good?  It's like they're trying to steal Jesus' thunder, man!

Then there's all these stories about how people just randomly converted to Islam.  But they're all second-hand, like, "So-and-so told me, who heard it from so-and-so..."  It's super shady, y'know?  They're trying to make it seem legit, but it just makes it look more suspicious.

The whole thing just feels off, like they're trying way too hard to make Muhammad look like some kind of perfect dude.  But history tells a different story, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today even know the real deal about Muhammad.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin'.  This whole Jesus thing, it's gone kinda haywire, ya know? Like, back in his day, it was all about love and peace, right? But then things got all mixed up, and now it's like a big, messy party with everyone bringing their own snacks and rules.  

Seems like folks are gettin' smarter these days, lookin' for somethin' real, somethin' true. The old ways, they ain't cuttin' it anymore.  The people who cling to the old ways, they're gonna be left behind, like a dusty record player in a digital world.


Mark my words, folks are gonna start lookin' back to the real deal, to what Jesus was all about.  They'll strip away all the extra stuff, all the layers that got added over time, and get back to the basics. It'll take a while, maybe even a whole heap of years, but it's gonna happen. It's like rewindin' a tape, goin' back to the start.  

It'll be a big shake-up, man. Churches might stay around, but they'll be different, like a classic car with a brand new engine.  Folks will be thinkin' alike more than ever, sharin' the same beliefs and beliefs, less of that "my way or the highway" stuff.

History's full of these kinda things, y'know?  Like how the Romans hated Christians, then turned around and became Christians themselves.  Or how we went from slavery in America to Black folks leadin' the way. It's like a big ol' cycle, man.  

This time, it's religion's turn for a makeover.  People are gonna ditch the fancy words and get down to what Jesus was really sayin'.  They'll realize that some of his stuff, it's more like a story, a way of teachin', not somethin' to take literally.

So, where did we go wrong? Well, it all started with the Jews, way back when.  They were the first ones with this whole "one God" thing, and they had their own ideas about how to worship. It wasn't all sunshine and rainbows, though. They had their own squabbles, their own groups, like the Sadducees, Pharisees, and those radical Zealots.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin' about this book, *The Jungle*. It's a real eye-opener, ya know? Shows ya how messed up people can be. Deep down, it's like they're all just greedy and selfish, only lookin' out for themselves. They don't care about nobody else, especially not the little guy.

Take those factory owners, for instance. All they care about is makin' a buck, makin' their businesses bigger and richer. They don't give a darn about the people workin' for 'em or the mess they're makin'.  Sinclair, the guy who wrote it, he describes these factories like they're monsters, all dark and smokin', spewin' out pollution everywhere.  It's like they don't even see the people or the animals gettin' hurt, just dollar signs.

And the workers? Forget about it! They're treated like dirt.  Workin' themselves to the bone, long hours, no breaks, and then BAM! Laid off with no warning, no help, nothin'.  It's a real dog-eat-dog world in there. 

There weren't no laws back then to protect 'em, so the bosses could do whatever they wanted. Speed up the line, make 'em work in dangerous conditions - didn't matter.  It's like they were slaves, stuck in a system with no way out.

Sinclair makes it clear that these poor folks were just expected to deal with it. No help, no support, just pure exploitation. Unions were supposed to help, but they just ended up makin' things worse.

So, like, picture this: authors, right? They're always tryin' to make ya feel somethin' when you read their stuff. Some ways are cooler than others, ya know? Like, F. Scott Fitzgerald in his book, *The Great Gatsby*, he's a master at this! He'll throw together words that don't usually hang out together, just to make ya feel a certain vibe. He also, like, uses symbols, ya dig? And he uses colors, man, like gold, green, white, gray, and red, to really make ya feel somethin'.

See, Fitzgerald, he builds up this whole thing about colors, like white and gray, and red and pink. And then, BAM! He uses 'em to make ya think about somethin' important in the story.

He uses white and gray to mean, like, bein' the same, ya know? Like, white is kinda fancier, and gray is more old-school and faded. He starts throwin' white and gray everywhere right from the start. Daisy and Jordan, they're always in white, man. Everyone's in white! Nick's wearin' white to Gatsby's party, Tom's got on a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine, she's all powdery white. The only time people ain't wearin' white is when Nick's checkin' out Gatsby's party, and then it's all crazy colors, man.

Fitzgerald keeps usin' white and gray for all sorts of stuff, like the boring parts of life. Nick goes to work, goes down "white chasms" in New York, people's names at Gatsby's party are just "gray names" on his list. Catherine's apartment's like a "white cake" of buildings, all the same. He even describes regular people and places as white or gray, like Daisy and Jordan's childhood, or the gray cars and land in the valley of ashes.

So, after Fitzgerald's thrown all this white and gray around, he uses it to show that somethin' ain't important. Like, when he describes Daisy in white, wearin' a white car, all of a sudden she doesn't seem like a real person anymore, more like somethin' Gatsby wants, somethin' that's just there, ya know?

Fitzgerald keeps doin' this with Daisy, makin' her seem more like an object than a person. He uses that gray haze around her fur collar, and she's always in white dresses. It's like he's sayin' she's just a symbol of somethin', not a real person.

Alright, lemme tell ya about this sweet spot in San Diego County.  Weather's always primo, so they grow all sorts of yummy stuff: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People here are crazy about organic food, like, there's a waiting list longer than my arm to get in on those fancy CSA programs.  And organic eggs and milk? Forget about it, those things fly off the shelves! 

Funny thing is, these organic farms aren't just about the grub. They're like mini-adventures! They'll give ya tours, let ya hike around, birdwatch, the whole shebang.  It's like a win-win, ya know? Makes the farmer some bank, keeps the critters happy, and gives folks a chance to learn something new.

Now,  organic farming ain't always a walk in the park. It takes more elbow grease, 'cause ya gotta deal with pests and weeds the old-fashioned way. And sometimes, ya lose more crops than if ya were using all those chemicals.  But hey, it's better for the planet, right? Plus, ya get more critters hangin' around, which is always a good thing.

So, picture this: we got a piece of land near Potrero, about 160 acres of chaparral, grasslands, and oak trees. It's right next to the big Cleveland National Forest, and it's packed with all sorts of cool critters, some of 'em even endangered!  

This land has seen a lot of history, too. Native Americans lived here for ages, then came the ranchers and wood cutters. It's been a homestead for ages, probably used for grazing and firewood.

I found this neat little organic farm nearby and figured, "Hey, what if we could do something like that?" So I looked into all the government programs out there to see how a small farmer could make it work. That's the gist of it!

Hey, so listen up, 'cause this is important stuff, especially if you're gonna be doin' any deal makin' with folks from outta town. See, every group of folks, they got their own way of doin' things, their own quirks, ya know? You can't just go around sayin' 'all Russians are stubborn' or 'all Japanese are easy goin''. That's just plain dumb. 

It's more like, try to figure out what makes 'em tick, what's important to 'em, and how that's gonna play out when you're sittin' down to talk business.  You're gonna see things through your own lens, sure, but try to look past that and really get a feel for their side.  It's like, learn their history, their hang-ups, the whole shebang. Don't go tryin' to change 'em, just roll with it, especially if you're the one with less to offer at the table.

Now, this ain't just about countries, either.  Every company, they got their own vibe, their own rules. Some are all about workin' late, others are more laid back. You see it in how they dress, how they talk, even who they hire. Some companies give a hoot about charity, others say 'stick to the company plan'. Even here in America, you see it everywhere, from one company to the next, city to city.

Values, those are the real deal. They're the 'why' behind everything. If they're all about savin' face or keepin' things peaceful, you better not go trashin' your boss or your own company just to win a deal.  And if they're all about hagglin' hard, don't expect 'em to fold easy.  

So, before you even step foot in that negotiatin' room, do your homework, learn the lay of the land. But don't forget, people are people, no matter where they're from. Get to know 'em, build a little rapport, that'll go a long way.

"A dumb guy once said, 'There ain't no God!'" Y'know, that's what Psalm 14 says in the Bible, and it's where St. Anselm started his big talk about God.  Thomas Aquinas, another smart dude, seems to think the same thing.  Since both of these guys are trying to prove the same God--the one from the Bible-- let's just go with that, okay?  We gotta keep things simple here.  Now, both of them make some pretty good points, but neither one of them really gives us a super solid reason to believe in God.

Let's start with St. Anselm. He's all about figuring things out through faith, like looking inside yourself to find proof of God. He says that since God's already in our minds, we can't really imagine him NOT being there.  It's kinda confusing when he explains it all fancy-like, but basically, he's saying we don't need to look anywhere else to find God--just look inside ourselves!  He's saying faith is like knowing something deep down even if you can't prove it.

Aquinas is way different. He thinks we can prove God exists just by using our brains and looking at the world around us.  No faith needed! This would be awesome for spreading the word about God, right?  People could just be convinced by logic instead of having to believe something without proof.  Aquinas has five big reasons why God must exist: stuff changes, stuff happens because something else made it happen, stuff just exists because something else caused it to exist, there are different levels of good and bad, and everything in the world is kinda organized like a puzzle. He says it all adds up to one thing: God exists!  It's like if you're missing a puzzle piece, you can still know it's there just by looking at the rest of the puzzle.

So, there was this dude, right? Back in the day, like way back, around the 500s BC. He was a prince, but later everyone called him Buddha. This guy, he got all deep and decided to ditch the whole fancy prince thing and figure out life's big mysteries. He ended up becoming super wise, like, totally enlightened. And guess what? His ideas started a whole religion called Buddhism. There's a bunch of different types of Buddhism, but this one's called Theravada, and it's the oldest one, kinda like the OG.

Now, Buddhism is like, super old—almost 2500 years!  Things have changed a lot since Buddha was around, even in places like Sri Lanka, where they still follow Theravada. They have this crazy water-cutting ceremony every year, and even though Buddha never mentioned anything about it, monks and regular folks join in. See, over time, Buddhism has changed a bunch, not just the little stuff like festivals, but even the big ideas.

There are a couple of important things to remember when we talk about Buddhism changing. First, there are "internal" changes, which come from Buddhists themselves, whether they're monks or not. Then there are "external" changes, which come from people outside Buddhism. Sometimes these changes are "hostile," meaning they try to hurt Buddhism, and sometimes they're "benign," meaning they don't really care about hurting or helping.

Alright, so let's get down to the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in three big things: the Buddha himself, his teachings (called the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (the Sangha). 

The Dhamma is basically a bunch of super old Buddhist texts called the Tripitaka. Think of it like a three-basket collection. One basket has stories and teachings of Buddha (the Suttas), another has rules for monks (the Vinaya), and the last one has deep, kinda philosophical stuff (the Abhidhamma).

The Abhidhamma talks about things like no-self (Anatta), suffering (Dukkha), and impermanence (Anicca).  These ideas are kinda mind-blowing, but they're like the keys to understanding how to escape the cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara).  

And guess what?  To escape Sansara, you gotta get rid of greed (lobha), anger (dosa), and delusion (moha).  You know, the usual stuff. Only when you're enlightened can you finally break free. 

The Vinaya tells everyone, monks and regular folks, how to live a good life. For regular folks, there are five basic rules: no killing, no lying, no stealing, no messing around sexually, and no drinking or doing drugs. Monks have a whole lot more rules to follow. 

But the most important thing in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths.  First, life is suffering (Dukkha). Second, suffering comes from wanting stuff (attachment). Third, you can stop suffering. And fourth, the way to stop suffering is by following the Eightfold Path.

So, get this, the US and Mexico have this crazy history, right? Like, picture this: a super intense rivalry that lasted for, like, 57 years! From 1836 to 1893, these two were always at each other's throats.  

It all kicked off with the Mexican-American War, where the US basically stomped all over Mexico and snatched up Texas and the Southwest. Talk about a bully! There were tons of other fights, but they finally cooled down right before World War I. 

Why did they hate each other so much? Well, they clashed over religion, culture, and all that jazz. Plus, they wanted the same stuff, which always leads to drama. It's like when you and your sibling fight over the last slice of pizza.

This rivalry thing isn't unique to them, though. Countries that live next door to each other often have beef, you know? It's like when you have a frenemy who lives next door and keeps borrowing your stuff without asking.

This guy, David Pletcher, said that the US had major problems with Mexico and Cuba, which makes sense because they're right next door. Meanwhile, other countries in Latin America have been chill with the US.

Religion was a big deal back then. Americans were all about freedom and stuff, while Mexico was super Catholic. It's like when your friend is obsessed with Harry Potter and you're more into Star Wars.

Things got heated because both countries inherited distrust from their past colonial days. It's like when your parents fight and you end up taking sides. 

These two nations had tons of disagreements, mostly about borders. Bandits and outlaws would cross the border and cause trouble, which is not cool.

Eventually, Mexico realized it needed the US, and the rivalry died down. The US shifted its focus from taking land to making money, which was a win for Mexico.

Fifteen years back, outta nowhere, I got hit with this illness, something I never even heard of.  I was a nurse, ya know, always thought I'd be a scientist or a reporter, maybe both, but I picked nursing 'cause it seemed safe, like a steady gig. "Always gonna need nurses, people always get sick," that kinda stuff. But there I was, 46, single, no dough, and couldn't work anymore.  Still can't, fifteen years later.  Living on Social Security Disability, I got nothin'. Barely gettin' by, day-to-day's a struggle, feelin' insecure and down on myself.  Nothing's for sure anymore, except this: I wouldn't have made it without my family and some good friends.  Let me tell ya, when the world goes sideways, strong doesn't cut it. 


Life throws curveballs, big and small.  You can plan all you want, but some stuff's just too much to handle alone.

Big government ain't the answer, that's for sure.  It's crumblin' apart, like a bad cake. But  maybe we gotta start trustin' each other again, helpin' out, not just fendin' for ourselves like cornered rats. Those folks back in the day, the ones who built this country, they didn't do it alone. They helped each other out, shared what they had. They had compassion, respect, and that's what got them through.


So yeah, be prepared. I am. Got my disaster kit, first aid stuff, water tablets, duct tape for the windows in case of a bio-attack, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, canned food, the whole shebang. If you got the space and know-how, grow your own food, can it, get a wood stove - good stuff. But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors. You never know when you'll need 'em.

Hey there, fellow shell enthusiasts! Ever wonder how those funky spirals on seashells end up looking the way they do? It's a real head-scratcher, right?  Back in the day, some smart guy named D'Arcy Thompson tried to figure it out using math, but it was like trying to solve a Rubik's Cube with your feet!  

Nowadays, we're using computer programs to model how shells change shape over time. Think of it like building a virtual seashell, tweaking the knobs and dials to see how it evolves. We're using these models to study a type of snail called Prunum.  We're taking X-rays of their shells to get all the juicy details, then feeding that info into a program called CerioShell. 

Basically, we're trying to figure out what the rules are for shell formation, kinda like figuring out the recipe for a perfect seashell cookie!  We're looking at how the whorls (those cool spiral parts) grow and change, how the aperture (the opening) moves, and all that jazz.  And get this, we're even checking out how all these changes happen over millions of years! 

It's like a shell detective story, except instead of clues, we've got math and X-rays.  Stay tuned for more shell-ebrity gossip!

Listen up, cuz I gotta tell ya 'bout this crazy situation in Indonesia.  For the last ten years,  the number of babies and new moms dying hasn't really changed much.  They're doin' alright on stuff like clean water and toilets, but when it comes to keeping the kiddies and moms healthy, they're lagging behind. We gotta figure out why this is happening 'cause just throwin' money at the problem ain't gonna cut it!

Now, they're braggin' 'bout more moms have doctors at their births, but let me tell ya, that ain't the whole story.  They're countin' folks like midwives who ain't really equipped to handle complications.  You know what that means?  Too many moms bleedin' to death 'cause they didn't get the right help.  And get this, fewer kids are even seein' doctors when they got the runs!  And postnatal care?  Forget about it, that's a mess too.

They ain't doin' enough C-sections either!  Only 4% compared to what they should be doin'.  And guess what?  In the city it's 7%, but out in the sticks it's a measly 2%!  That's right, folks in the city get way better care than the folks in the country.  And it's even worse for the poorest folks. They're strugglin' to get any help 'cause they can't afford it.

So what's the solution?  Should they just focus on a few programs or fix the whole dang healthcare system?  Programs seem easier, faster, and more focused.  But here's the catch, if you focus on one thing, you forget about everything else.  You end up with a bunch of programs doin' the same thing and nobody knows who's doin' what.  It's a mess!

Okay, so, listen up! Victorian books are all about the fancy stuff and the rich folks, right? But get this, there are these two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," that are like, totally different. They're still from the Victorian times, but they're all mysterious and kinda spooky, which wasn't really a thing back then. It makes the characters way more interesting, 'cause you get to see their secrets and how they feel about stuff. 

Take this part from "Oliver Twist," for example:

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)


These two books, they use mystery a lot, especially in dreams and stuff. In "Oliver Twist," Oliver's dreams tell us about how he's feeling inside, what hurts him, and what he really thinks about everything going on. 

When they finally show what happened when Oliver got shot in chapter 28, he relives it like a dream, even though he's trying to get help. It shows how much control Oliver *doesn't* have. He's in so much pain, he doesn't even notice when someone carries him away. It's like his pain is so bad that it's all he can focus on. It makes you wonder who's really in charge here, because it's definitely not Oliver.  He just kinda accepts everything that happens to him.

The shooting is a big deal because it shows how broken Oliver is. It's like Fagin broke him, made him give up and accept this awful life. 


In "Wuthering Heights," they do this dreamy, mysterious thing too, but it's different. 


"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."

Okay, so picture this: a couple years back, I was working with these little kids after school, helping them with their homework. I was pretty good at English and reading, so that's what I mostly focused on.  One kid, this little guy named Adrian, he was in like third or fourth grade, was having a real rough time reading. It was super weird, he knew some letters perfectly, but others?  Like, totally clueless.  It didn't make sense! He spoke perfect English, but reading, not so much.  So we were stuck in this loop, struggling, until one day Adrian's mom came to pick him up. She didn't speak a lick of English, just Spanish.   I was just starting to learn Spanish myself, so we managed to piece together a conversation. And then, BAM! It hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet well. I don't know if that helped him much in the long run, but I hope he's doing better now. 

I tell this story because it shows how messed up the language barrier can be in schools, especially here in California. It's not always as obvious as we think.  Even if a kid speaks English fluently, reading can still be a total nightmare.  Everyone knows this is a problem, right? So what do we do about it? For Adrian, it was simple: English reading tutoring, focusing on the alphabet and sounds. But for kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. There's no one magic answer.  Dual language systems, immersion programs, private tutors, ESL classes, none of them are going to fix everything on their own. We need to mix and match! 

First off, dual language programs are awesome. They're not just for kids who speak Spanish, they're for everyone!  Studies show that kids in these programs do way better in school. There's this whole fear that it's a waste of money and resources, that most kids won't benefit. But that's just not true! If we made these programs the norm instead of the exception, everyone would win. 

So how do we do it? Do we force all teachers to be bilingual?  No way! That's crazy. But what if we had bilingual helpers, tutors, whatever you wanna call them? That makes perfect sense, right?

Alright, check it out.  You ever hear that, like, there's something way bigger than us out there?  Stuff you can't even wrap your head around?  Some folks go to church, some hit up the temple, others just try to figure it out on their own.  Lotsa people just go with what their parents told 'em, y'know?  But some folks, they say, "Nope, that ain't for me!" They think their own little world is all that matters.  We change our minds about stuff all the time, right?  What's important today might not be tomorrow.  But we're all tryin' to figure out who we are, what it all means.  We're lookin' for something to guide us through the darkness, somethin' to shine a light on the way.

My old man, he loved cardinals.  We were sittin' on the porch one day, rain comin' down like crazy.  Tin roof was bangin' like a drum.  We were smokin' cigarettes, him lookin' out at the storm, like he was searchin' for somethin'.  He was skinny, clothes saggin' on him.  Hair was gettin' thin, too.  Didn't look at me much, just stared at the rain.  I felt kinda lost, scared even.  Couldn't bring myself to talk about how much I was gonna miss him, 'cause sayin' it out loud would make it feel real, y'know?  So I just hugged him, moved my chair closer, and looked out at the rain with him.

He kicked the bucket in December, five days after I turned twenty-two.  Chemo and radiation, they didn't take away his pain, just stretched it out longer than the doctors thought.  What good was that, I don't know.  What kinda God makes that happen?  I didn't pray that night.  If there was a God out there, I figured he wasn't listenin' anymore.

I didn't wanna see him die.  Couldn't bear to watch the life that made me slip away.  I wanted to remember him how he was, not how he ended.  Besides, I knew him better than anyone else, better than his family even.  And I knew he wouldn't want me there, watchin' him fade away.  So I hid in my bed for three days, waitin' for the news.

Didn't get a call.  Not a peep.

Let's talk about those spooky old books we call Gothic Novels. They're kinda like a mixed-up word puzzle, like "old" and "new" mashed together, you know?  This is what that book-smart guy Ian Watt said, anyway.  People have always gone back and forth about these Gothic stories - some say they're all smoke and mirrors, others say they're super deep and make you feel all tingly inside. 

It all started with a guy named Horace Walpole and his story, "The Castle of Otranto." He mixed up old-timey drama with what was happening in stories *now*.  Think of it like taking a bunch of cool old stuff and putting it in a brand new package. It was like, "Hey, check out this spooky castle from way back when, but with all the new-fangled stuff we're doing in stories today!"

Back then, the word "Gothic" was kind of a dirty word.  It meant old-fashioned and not as cool as the shiny new stuff. But Walpole got clever and used it to make something totally unique.  He took all those old theatre tricks and fancy castle stuff and threw it into a story where you get inside the characters' heads.

So, what makes these Gothic stories so cool? Well, one big thing is this idea of "Chivalry."  You know, knights, brave and honorable and all that.  This was a big deal back in the Gothic days, and Walpole wanted to show how awesome it was. He thought maybe the world had forgotten about chivalry and it was time to bring it back!  He had this character, Frederic, who was the perfect knight.  He had all the fancy clothes, the tragic backstory, and the brave heart.  It was like a fairytale come to life, but with a spooky twist.

Alright, listen up, 'cause I'm gonna break down this whole "supply chain management" thing for ya. It's basically how we get stuff from the moment someone wants it, all the way back to the raw materials, and then how we make it and send it to them, you know, the whole shebang! This fancy name was cooked up in 1982 by this guy, Keith Oliver. He said it's all about planning, doing it, and making sure everything runs smooth so customers get what they need, fast and efficient, like clockwork! 

There are six key parts to this whole supply chain thing: production, getting the stuff, keeping it in stock, figuring out where everything goes, moving it around, and sharing info. Managers use these six things to make sure customers are happy as clams.

First up, you got production. That's the heart of the whole operation. It's all about figuring out when, where, and how to make stuff. Managers gotta know what people want, right?  So they look at the market, see what's hot and what's not. Once they know what customers crave, they decide what to make and how much. Then comes the "where" part - which plant is best for making what? Managers gotta think about volume, quality, and making sure customers are stoked. 

Once they got the location figured out, it's time to schedule work and keep the machinery in tip-top shape. Production is super important, every little detail matters. Mess something up, and you could be lookin' at wasted time and money down the road. I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, and lemme tell ya, those places have processes for everything, from how employees dress to how they unload trucks. It's all about keepin' things smooth and runnin' like a well-oiled machine.

Next up is supply. It's all about making smart decisions about what a company can do itself and what to hand off to other companies. Sometimes you got different parts of production for one product, each with its own tools, workers, and specialties. Managers gotta pick the best fit for each part of the process. Outsourcing is another big one - handing off work to other companies to speed things up, keep costs down, and be flexible. Basically, it's about gettin' the job done right while keepin' things cost-effective.

So, picture this: Ellen Page, you know, the chick from Juno? She's on a street corner, holdin' up this cardboard sign with a crazy message scrawled on it. It says, "Hitler is alive in Burma!"

Now, Burma, that's also known as Myanmar, right? It's this country in Southeast Asia run by some seriously nasty dudes who took over in 1962. Like, total power grab, coup d'état style. Anyway, back in 2007, these monks decided they'd had enough. They started these protests, the first in ages. They called it the "Saffron Revolution" 'cause they wore these orange robes, get it?

At first, the government was like, "Whatever, monks, go protest." But then things got outta hand. People started joining in, and it turned into a full-blown brawl between the monks and the military.  They were bashin' up monasteries, throwin' people in jail, even killin' journalists just for showin' up.  

This ain't new, though.  Governments tryin' to squash anyone who disagrees? Been happenin' forever. Like, remember the Roman emperors? They thought they were gods, right? And those Japanese emperors? They're like, literally gods, sent to bring us... Motorola phones and, uh, hara-kiri? And don't even get me started on our own president, George W. Bush.  Seriously, he's buddies with Ted Haggard, the head honcho of Stupid People Worldwide, which sounds like a joke but it's actually a thing.  

Then there was that Tiananmen Square thing in '89.  Students, intellectuals, everyone was out there sayin' "Enough!" But the government shut it down real hard.  They say 200-300 people died, but who knows?  And the Rwandan genocide?  Total nightmare. Hutu guys went on a rampage, killin' Tutsis and anyone who dared to stand up to them.  And, of course, there's Hitler's whole "Final Solution" thing.  Talk about messed up.

So, get this, Duke Ellington was a total rockstar in jazz.  He played for ages and was always coming up with new stuff for his band.  Sure, he wasn't always the flashiest piano player, but he wrote some seriously awesome tunes that let everyone in the band shine.

He was like this genius architect, building these musical houses where soloists could go wild and improvise, while still keeping everything tight and groovy.  He knew how to make each player sound their best, and he could make the whole orchestra sound totally unique, like a one-of-a-kind instrument. That's how he came up with some of the coolest jazz ever!

This one song, "Creole Love Call," is a perfect example.  He used a voice like a real instrument, adding texture and color without any words.  It's like he knew how to make every sound sing, not just the instruments.

And get this, he wrote this song with this awesome call-and-response thing going on between the voice and the reeds.  It starts smooth and mellow, then gets all rough and edgy.  Then there's a trumpet solo that's all mellow and bluesy, and a clarinet solo that's super high and fast.  The whole thing builds and builds until it's a total explosion of sound!

He did the same thing with this song "Hot and Bothered." He had this trumpet player, Bubber Miley, doing this awesome muted trumpet thing, and this singer, Baby Cox, scatting like crazy.  It's like they were trading ideas back and forth, creating this amazing mix of sounds.  And then there's "It Don't Mean a Thing If It Ain't Got That Swing." He had this trombone player, Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, who played the melody on this muted trombone, and it was just killer!

Ellington was a total genius.  He knew how to make every sound count, and he knew how to make music that was both exciting and moving.

She had this gnawing feeling, like something was missing. It started back when she was 14, just starting to figure out this whole being a teenager thing. And three years later, at 17, it was still there. She'd figured out she wanted someone, not some shiny object, but no boys really grabbed her attention. Some tried, going all awkward and lovey-dovey, but nobody clicked. She'd spend days pondering this, trying to figure out why she was so different. Theories popped up, but nothing stuck. So she just kept going, life unfolding with this big question mark hanging over her.

Her days usually went pretty chill. Her folks were cool, calm, never fought. Arguments with her were rare, mostly about her being, well, her - loud, energetic, a total personality explosion.  

But today wasn't chill. She was bouncing around the house, trying to find some spark for her creative stuff, when a yelp from the kitchen stopped her dead. Her mom's voice, shaky and panicked. "Mom?! What's wrong?" she rushed in, heart pounding. There she was, sprawled on the floor, wincing with every breath. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need to go to the hospital," her mom gasped.  Her daughter wasted no time. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where to pick you up!" Her mom pointed, and the daughter, secretly thankful she'd been toughening herself up at the gym, scooped her mom up and got them to the car.

The hospital smelled like antiseptic and worry, but all her daughter could focus on was her mom. She practically dragged her inside, yelling for a doctor. Faces swarmed, someone wheeled in a bed, and her mom was whisked away. Her daughter sat there, anxiety buzzing.

Turned out, her mom had been reaching for a vase on the top shelf, slipped off a stool, and BAM!

Alright, so picture this: Researchers wanted to see if following a "Mediterranean Diet" – lotsa fruits, veggies, fish, and healthy fats – would keep ya heart healthy and help ya avoid strokes. They had this special score, called the "alternate Mediterranean" (aMed) score, to measure how well folks stuck to the diet.  

They already kinda knew that this diet was good for ya, but they wanted to focus on strokes this time. Think of it like comparing a regular soda to a diet soda. Both are kinda sugary, but the diet one's supposed to be better for you.

So, they followed over 74,000 nurses for 20 years. Every few years, these nurses filled out questionnaires about what they ate. It's like a super detailed "What's in your fridge?" survey. 

These researchers made sure to check if the nurses' answers were accurate by comparing them to other records. They also took into account things like smoking, weight, exercise, and whether or not they took vitamins.

They found that ladies who scored high on the aMed diet quiz were way less likely to have heart attacks or strokes. It's like they were winning at the heart health game! 

So yeah, this Mediterranean diet thing seems like a pretty good way to keep your ticker in tip-top shape!

Man, lemme tell ya about this crazy time back in 2007. The whole country was screwin' up big time. Jobs vanished faster than a robot bunny after I kick it, and houses were worth less than a chewed-up chew toy. Even the big, fancy companies were crumblin' like stale cookies.  It was a mess, a real doozy!

Turns out, all this started 'cause some folks in charge made some real dumb decisions. They pushed banks and companies to hand out these loans, called sub-prime loans, to folks who probably shouldn't have had 'em. These loans were like a ticking time bomb, see? And with these Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac guys, they were packin' these bad loans into these fancy packages and sellin' 'em off like hotcakes.

But here's the kicker: when folks couldn't pay back those loans, BAM! The whole system went kablooey! Banks were broke, the markets were crashin', and everyone was lookin' around like, "What just happened?!"

It all started way back in 1999, when that Clinton fella was tryin' to stay in power. He wanted everyone happy, so he loosened up the rules on lending.  Little did he know, it was like lettin' a robot bunny loose in a china shop. Disaster, I tell ya!

Then, these fancy new mortgages came along, all complicated and confusing.  Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, collateralized debt obligations... they sounded like somethin' outta a sci-fi movie! But they were makin' folks borrow more and more money, and it was all tied up in the housing market. Like a giant web of debt, and when that web started to unravel...well, let's just say it wasn't pretty.

The housing bubble burst, and the whole system went belly up. Banks went bankrupt, big companies were sold off cheap, and the government had to step in and clean up the mess. It was a real rollercoaster ride, and it took years for things to start gettin' better.

Alright, let's talk about exposition. It's that part of your story where you get to show off your writing skills, right?  You paint pictures with words, make your readers gasp in awe, maybe even shed a tear or two.  Or, you know, it's the part where your readers start yawning and hitting the "back" button faster than a cheetah on speed.  Even Dr. Merlin, the queen of storytelling herself, has been known to yell at her computer screen when she's drowning in a sea of "tell, don't show."

Exposition, my friends, is not your best friend. 

You already know the golden rule: "Show, don't tell." But sometimes, even the best writers slip up and end up writing pages and pages of nothing happening, or worse, too much happening.  It's like that little voice in your head whispering, "Just get all the boring stuff out of the way so we can get to the good part!" But that voice is a sneaky little devil, always tempting you to overload your readers with unnecessary details about every character's childhood and every insignificant event.

Think about it: exposition is like that scene in a movie where one character simply dumps a ton of information on another, like a cheesy version of "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In writing, it's the author doing the telling instead of showing.

Here's a simple example.  Let's say you're reading a story and suddenly you're told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain time and place, got married in a big fancy ceremony, and then, BAM! He's murdered right in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire life-changing saga to take up two pages, with both characters only getting two lines of dialogue each. You'd want to feel the love between them, see it in their actions and words, understand why the heroine is so devastated.

A good introduction to the husband's character would allow you to connect with him emotionally, mourn his death with her, and understand the depth of their love. You'd feel invested in her pain.

In short, you'd want the author to give you more than just the bare bones of the story: "They met, they married, he died."  You want the juicy details, the emotional depth, the "meat on the bone," so to speak.


Sometimes, it's tempting to rush past details about your characters, like that night manager at the gas station who used to be in the Air Force, got married twice, no kids, loves fishing, secretly wants to own the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Give your readers a glimpse into his soul!
