Man, being a brother is wild, ya know? It's like this super strong connection, like, you get each other in a way nobody else can. It's got all sorts of feelings mixed up in it, like love, pride, even jealousy and anger sometimes. You see yourself in your brother, more than anyone else. It's like lookin' in a mirror, except it's a mirror that shows ya the real you, the good and the bad. And when things get tough, that bond really shines, whether it's for good or for bad.

But here's the thing, all those feelings come with a price, you know? Like, you gotta deal with the mess they make. When you look your brother dead in the eye and see yourself back at ya, it's like you see yourself clear as day, not how people think you are, but how you really are. It's in your actions and what happens because of them that you see your true colors.

That's what this story, "The Scarlet Ibis," is all about. Two brothers, they're out there in this beautiful place, but they're on this crazy journey that's doomed from the start. It's all about pride and disappointment clashing, and in the end, only one brother walks away. You see it all through the main guy, Doodle, and how he sees his brother. He sees the world through his own messed up feelings, and that shapes everything he does.

The main guy, he's all about pride, from the start. He wanted a brother who was tough, who could keep up with him, who could do all the cool stuff he dreamed of. But Doodle, well, he was born different. He was weak, and it was clear he wasn't gonna be the brother the main guy had in mind.  It made the main guy angry, even made him think about doing something awful. But then Doodle smiles, and the main guy's heart softens. He loves his brother, even if he doesn't always show it.

Yo, check it! So, our brains are like, totally wild, right? They're constantly buzzin' with info, like a super-charged computer. Back in the day, folks thought our brains were like wax tablets or papyrus scrolls, you know, the old-school stuff. Then, they started comparing them to books, and now, it's all about computers. But here's the deal:  these comparisons are cool, but they can also be misleading, so don't take 'em too seriously.

Imagine your senses, like your eyes, ears, and skin, as input devices, taking in all the crazy stuff around you. They turn all those sights, sounds, smells, and feels into signals your brain can understand. Then, your brain, it's like a mad scientist, throwing these signals around, analyzing them from every angle. It's like a mix of bottom-up and top-down processing, where your brain builds up a picture from the basic details and also uses what it already knows to make sense of things faster. Like, say you see a black box on a white background. Your brain zooms in on the details: the color, the shape, the edges. It's all bottom-up. But, 'cause your brain's a genius, it also uses what it already knows about boxes to figure out it's a box, not some weird white hole. That's top-down processing in action.

Now, your brain's got this super important filter called attention. It decides what's important and what can chill. It's like a bouncer at a club, letting in the VIPs and keeping out the riff-raff. So, while your brain's processing every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, your attention filter's like, "Nah, we don't need to know that level of detail." But, if someone yells your name in a crowded room, bam, your attention's all over it.

And get this, your brain's got different memory banks: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory's like a super-fast snapshot, holding info for a split second. Working memory's like your mental scratchpad, holding onto info for a bit longer, about 20 seconds or so. Long-term memory's the big kahuna, storing all your memories for years, maybe even a lifetime.

So, how's all this knowledge organized in your brain? That's a question scientists are still trying to figure out. Some think it's like a network, with different concepts connected like nodes. Imagine, "chair" linked to "table," which is linked to "wooden," and so on.

Okay, so picture this: Aldous Huxley is freaking out about technology and how money runs everything. He wrote this book "Brave New World" to show us what happens when we get too obsessed with happiness and being part of the crowd. In this world, people are basically robots who just want to have fun and don't care about anything else.

They're controlled by this big boss guy called the World Controller, who makes sure everyone stays happy and doesn't think too much about the system. It's like a giant game, and the people are just pawns.

Think about Marxism, man. Huxley is totally throwing shade at capitalism in this book. He's talking about how people are brainwashed into thinking that buying stuff and being part of the group is all that matters. They don't even realize they're being controlled! 

The book is like a big warning about how capitalism can make people lose their freedom and individuality. It's like they're all trapped in a big, happy bubble, but it's all fake.  They're just following the rules and buying stuff, and they don't even know it.

And get this, there's no real love or emotion in this world. People just hook up for fun and don't care about each other. It's all superficial and fake. The characters are so shallow, it's like Huxley is saying that capitalism is sucking the soul out of humanity.

So yeah, Huxley is basically saying that if we keep going down this path of technology and consumerism, we're all gonna become robots who are controlled by the system.

Alright, lemme tell ya about this gig I've got at this joint called University Park. Been here for a hot minute, like two and a half years, which is, like, four and a half semesters. 

Getting around this place can be a real pain in the neck, lemme tell ya. My freshman year, they stuck me in these dorms called East Halls, which were way out on the edge of campus, like, past the stadium and that big Bryce Jordan Center thing.  

Man, going from my digs in Stuart Hall to classes way over by Willard, which is kinda in the middle of all this, could take, like, 25 minutes on foot. And forget about it if the weather was acting up, 'cause State College weather is, like, the worst.

I was shootin' the breeze with this guy who graduated not that long ago, and he told me that back in the day, East Halls was like miles away from everything else.  There was just, like, this huge empty space between them and the rest of the school. Now, that space is filled with sports fields, new buildings like that fancy Creamery and that new health place, and apartments everywhere. It's like they just keep building and building, and it's getting harder and harder to get from one spot to another.

So, what's the answer? Well, I'll tell ya, it's gotta be bikes. Bikes are the way to go. But, ya know, it's not just about having bikes. The campus itself needs to be built with bikes in mind.

Last week I was talkin' to this dude who got back into bikin' after, like, years. He told me he didn't know why he ever stopped. "Bikes are the best," he said. "For a while, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around."

Besides bein' good for ya, bikes are the quickest way to travel. A little oatmeal and a little pedalin' can take ya 30 miles or more.  

I'm livin' off campus now, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest thing I did this year was buy a bike. Every day, I gotta go to Thomas building for class, which is, like, a 25-minute walk from my place. But on my bike, I can get there in 5 minutes if I really pump those pedals.

The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas, but it ain't always the easiest ride.  

Walkin' ain't bad, but I'm just too busy to walk everywhere. If I didn't have my bike, I'd be walkin' all the time. Walkin' to Thomas every day would steal, like, 30-40 minutes outta my day. That's like, two and a half hours every week. Plus, all the other walkin' I'd have to do for other classes, appointments, and stuff.  Where'd I find the time for that?
